{"id":"northwest-passage-scenic-byway","generatedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z","designation":"All-American Road","parkCode":null,"source":{"roadArticle":"U.S. Route 12 in Idaho","revisionId":1334783938,"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/U.S._Route_12_in_Idaho"},"attribution":{"license":"CC BY-SA 4.0","licenseUrl":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/","articleUrl":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/U.S._Route_12_in_Idaho","text":"Route, junction, and history details adapted from the Wikipedia article \"U.S. Route 12 in Idaho\", by Wikipedia contributors, licensed under CC BY-SA 4.0."},"sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia","src":"wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/U.S._Route_12_in_Idaho","revisionId":1334783938,"retrievedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z"},{"name":"Federal Highway Administration — National Scenic Byways","src":"fhwa","url":"https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/byways","retrievedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z"},{"name":"OpenStreetMap contributors (ODbL)","src":"osm","url":"https://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright","retrievedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z"}],"endpoints":{"from":"46.41,-117.02","to":"Lolo Pass, ID","via":["Lewiston, ID","Greer, ID","Kamiah, ID"]},"itinerary":[{"seq":1,"place":"Snake River","state":"ID","kind":"terminus","mileFromStart":0,"toNextMi":2.6,"note":"The drive begins here","control":["Walla Walla","Interstate Highway Bridge"],"lat":46.7324,"lng":-117.03983,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":2,"place":"Lewiston","state":"ID","kind":"town","mileFromStart":2.6,"toNextMi":49,"note":"Junction toward Port Districts","control":["Port Districts","Moscow","Coeur d'Alene"],"lat":46.70924,"lng":-116.86615,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":3,"place":"Greer","state":"ID","kind":"town","mileFromStart":51.6,"toNextMi":14.6,"note":"Junction toward Weippe & Pierce","control":["Weippe","Pierce"],"lat":46.76447,"lng":-116.66395,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":4,"place":"Kamiah","state":"ID","kind":"town","mileFromStart":66.2,"toNextMi":108.2,"note":"Junction toward Nezperce","control":["Nezperce"],"lat":46.78282,"lng":-116.17907,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":5,"place":"Lolo Pass","state":"ID","kind":"terminus","mileFromStart":174.4,"toNextMi":null,"note":"The drive ends here","control":["Missoula"],"lat":null,"lng":null,"src":"wikipedia"}],"history":{"paragraphs":["US-12 was created in 1925 as part of the original system of U.S. Highways, and its original western terminus was in Miles City, Montana. In 1962, the highway was extended west to Lewiston, ending at the former US-410. In 1967, it was extended to its current western terminus in Aberdeen, Washington, with the Idaho section taking its current route.","The Lewis and Clark Highway, from Lewiston eastward to Lolo Pass, was designated SH-9 in 1916 and construction began in 1920. Federal prison labor was used in the late 1930s to early 1940s, and Japanese internment labor was used during the last two years of World War II, working out of the Kooskia Internment Camp, six miles (9.7 km) upstream of Lowell, just below milepost 104.","By late 1955, 27 miles (43 km) remained unfinished, and, upon its completion in 1962, it was redesignated US 12. At the dedication ceremony at Lolo Pass attended by thousands on August 19, the states' governors, Robert E. Smylie of Idaho and Tim Babcock of Montana, cut through a ceremonial western redcedar log at Packers Meadow with a two-man crosscut saw.","The bridge crossing the Clearwater River near Arrow opened for traffic in early 1973. The route previously was on the river's south bank between the bridge and Spalding, where it crossed on the old Spalding bridge; damaged by ice jams 10 years earlier, it was dismantled shortly after the Arrow bridge opened."],"sourceSection":"History","src":"wikipedia"},"highlights":[{"n":"Snake River","d":"The drive begins here","q":"Snake River","lat":46.41,"lng":-117.02,"src":"wikipedia"}],"references":[{"n":1,"text":"Idaho Transportation Department. \"Milepost Log, US 12\" (PDF). Archived (PDF) from the original on February 4, 2017. Retrieved June 3, 2017.","url":"http://apps.itd.idaho.gov/apps/milepointlog/logs/usHW/US_12_MPLog.pdf"},{"n":2,"text":"\"Northwest Passage Scenic Byway\". Idaho's Scenic Byways. Archived from the original on June 25, 2013.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20130625043123/http://www.idahobyways.gov/byways/northwest-passage.aspx"},{"n":3,"text":"\"US-12: Clearwater Memorial Bridge\". Idaho Transportation Department Projects. Archived from the original on January 27, 2024. Retrieved January 28, 2024.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20240127234753/https://itdprojects.org/projects/us12memorialbridge/"},{"n":4,"text":"Idaho Transportation Department (May 26, 2005). \"Idaho Highway Historical Marker Guide Index\". Archived from the original on December 15, 2008. Retrieved January 11, 2009.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20081215223302/http://itd.idaho.gov/hmg/SignIndx.htm"},{"n":5,"text":"National Park Service (November 20, 1999). \"Spalding Site\". Archived from the original on January 3, 2009. Retrieved January 11, 2009.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20090103111131/http://www.nps.gov/archive/nepe/spalding1a.htm"},{"n":6,"text":"\"Traffic may be moving across new Arrow bridge by November\". Lewiston Morning Tribune. September 23, 1972. p. 16. Archived from the original on September 14, 2021. Retrieved January 21, 2020.","url":"https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=r4xfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mzAMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6214%2C5174221"},{"n":7,"text":"\"New route\". Lewiston Morning Tribune. November 20, 1972. p. 12. Archived from the original on September 14, 2021. Retrieved May 3, 2020.","url":"https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=d4JfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=lTAMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6139%2C5583700"},{"n":8,"text":"\"Bridge opens\". Spokane Daily Chronicle. February 21, 1973. p. 5. Archived from the original on May 12, 2016. Retrieved January 21, 2020.","url":"https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=BKNYAAAAIBAJ&sjid=m_gDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4751%2C1653598"}],"routeLine":[[46.7324,-117